        <p>A quick note on how to think about these: the goal isn't to hide that you have kids — it's to find platforms where people self-select for being open to it, and to present your situation honestly from the start. Filtering early saves everyone time.</p>

        <div class="platform-cards">

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">Best overall</span>
            <h3>Match.com</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: serious relationships, 30s–50s</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Longest-established paid platform — self-selects for people who mean it</li>
              <li>Profile includes kids status prominently — filters work both ways</li>
              <li>Larger pool than niche sites, more geographic reach</li>
              <li>Better messaging than swipe-only apps — actual conversations</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit Match.com →</a>
          </article>

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">Most popular right now</span>
            <h3>Hinge</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: 30s, relationship-minded users</p>
            <ul>
              <li>"Designed to be deleted" — positioned toward real relationships</li>
              <li>Kids section on profile is prominent and filterable</li>
              <li>Prompt-based profiles show personality better than photos alone</li>
              <li>Free tier is usable; paid tier significantly improves reach</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit Hinge →</a>
          </article>

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">Single parents only</span>
            <h3>SingleParentMeet</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: meeting people who are already in the same boat</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Everyone on this platform has kids — no explanation needed</li>
              <li>Smaller pool but higher shared-context relevance</li>
              <li>Good for dads who want to date another single parent specifically</li>
              <li>Part of the People Media network (same as Match)</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit SingleParentMeet →</a>
          </article>

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">Women initiate</span>
            <h3>Bumble</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: dads who want a lower-pressure dynamic</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Women message first — tends to produce more intentional matches</li>
              <li>Kids information visible on profile</li>
              <li>Large user base, especially in cities</li>
              <li>Bumble BFF mode available if you're also looking for social connection</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit Bumble →</a>
          </article>

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">Compatibility-focused</span>
            <h3>eHarmony</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: dads who want a structured, compatibility-first process</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Matches based on detailed compatibility questionnaire</li>
              <li>Skews toward people looking for long-term relationships</li>
              <li>Higher upfront time investment, but typically fewer wasted matches</li>
              <li>Kids/family goals factored into compatibility matching</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit eHarmony →</a>
          </article>

          <article class="platform-card">
            <span class="platform-badge">50+</span>
            <h3>OurTime</h3>
            <p class="platform-best-for">Best for: single dads 50 and older</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Designed specifically for the 50+ dating pool</li>
              <li>Age-appropriate community — no need to compete with 25-year-olds</li>
              <li>Adult children and grandchildren situations well-represented</li>
              <li>Simpler interface than younger-skewing apps</li>
            </ul>
            <a href="#" class="platform-cta" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Visit OurTime →</a>
          </article>

        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>On your profile:</strong> mention your kids. Don't bury it, don't over-explain it — just include it the way you'd include any other important fact about your life. People who are open to it will keep reading. People who aren't will filter themselves out. That's the system working correctly.</p>
        </div>

